      "task1": "The chart shows how the percentage of households living in owned and rented homes in England and Wales changed from 1918 to 2011. In 1918, most people rented their homes, about 77%, while only around 23% owned them. Over the years, the number of homeowners increased steadily, while renting became less common. By 1971, the percentages were almost equal, and after that, home ownership continued to rise. The highest point was in 2001, when about 69% of households owned their homes. However, by 2011, ownership slightly fell to 64%, and renting rose again to 36%. Overall, the main trend is a clear shift from renting to owning over the 20th century, though there was a small decline in ownership at the end of the period",
      "task2": "Some people think technology has made life more complicated because it creates dependence and constant distractions. For example, people spend too much time on their phones, checking messages or social media, which can cause stress and reduce real communication. Also, new devices and apps are updated so often that users must always learn how to use them, making life feel more tiring. On the other hand, many believe technology has made life easier. It helps people work faster, connect instantly, and access information anytime. For instance, online banking, smart home devices, and navigation apps save both time and effort in daily life. In my opinion, technology itself is not the problem; it depends on how people use it. If used wisely, it simplifies life and increases convenience, but if overused, it can definitely make life more complicated"
